cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SY, cs.MM, cs.AI 

Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper deals with predicting the impact of an emitter on different geographic locations, which involves information theory concepts such as channel capacity and signal-to-noise ratio. 
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture): The paper discusses the deployment of fixed sensors to sample the RF environment and the use of interpolation methods to infer received power at locations between sensors, which are relevant to networking and internet architecture. 
3. cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper proposes a radio map interpolation method that aims to minimize the RMS errors in predicted dB-power, which involves control theory concepts such as optimization and feedback. 
4. cs.MM (Multimedia): The paper deals with spatial sampling of the RF environment and interpolation methods, which are relevant to multimedia applications such as wireless video streaming. 
5. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence): The paper proposes a radio map interpolation method that exploits the known properties of most path loss models, which involves machine learning concepts such as feature extraction and pattern recognition.
